    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-02-18T17:50:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-02-18T17:50:00-05:00" n="655"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d655">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">357.AB/2–1852: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United Nations</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_AWR1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Austin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d655fn1">This telegram was repeated by the Department to New
                        Delhi and Karachi.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-02-18T17:50:00-05:00"
                            >February 18, 1952—5:50 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>543. From <persName corresp="#p_GEA1">Gross</persName>. Re Kashmir. Have just
                    seen No. 2851, Feb 12, from New Delhi re Kashmir and in particular <gloss
                        target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> expression concern re implications my talk with
                        <persName corresp="#p_ASM1">Sheikh Abdullah</persName> (reported <gloss
                        target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 1309, Feb 6).</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> aware that for over two years <gloss
                        target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> has studied case with UN <gloss
                        target="#t_REP1">rep</gloss>s McNaughton,<note n="2" xml:id="d655fn2">Gen.
                        A. G. L. McNaughton of Canada, President of the Security Council in December
                        1949, negotiated informally with Representatives of India and Pakistan. His
                        final report to the Council, dated Feb. 3, 1950 (UN doc. S/1453), which
                        included a plan for demilitarization, was accepted by Pakistan but rejected
                        by India (UN docs. S/PV. 463–466, Feb. 7–10, 1950).</note>
                    <persName>Dixon</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName> as
                    well as with <gloss target="#t_REP1">rep</gloss>s of both parties, including
                        <persName corresp="#p_KCSM1">Zafrullah</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_AM2">Mohammed Ali</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_KGMA1"
                        >Ayub</persName> for <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_RSBN1"
                        >Rau</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MVKK1">Menon</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DR1">Dayal</persName> and others for <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                        >GOI</gloss>.</p>
                <p>I profoundly hope <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> New Delhi gives no
                    indications to <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> or to <persName
                        corresp="#p_ASM1">Abdullah</persName> at this stage that any solution other
                    than state-wide plebiscite following demilitarization is envisaged even as
                    residual possibility. From beginning it has seemed of extreme importance to
                        <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> (dealing with both sides and with
                    impartial UN <gloss target="#t_REP1">rep</gloss>s) that parties be firmly held
                    to their agreement until and unless it is superseded by mutually acceptable
                    alternative.</p>
                <p>In his conversation with me in Paris, <persName corresp="#p_ASM1"
                        >Abdullah</persName> was clearly shopping for bargains. I fear that quickest
                    way really to destroy UN prestige in this case would be to weaken <persName
                        corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName>’s authority by permitting doubts to
                    arise now concerning our firm intention to throw our weight behind compliance
                    with agreements already reached between parties. I believe it is premature to
                    say that <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> should accept <persName
                        corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName>’s failure as “clear evidence futility
                    seeking solution through demilitarization and all-Kashmir plebiscite”. After
                    all, this solution represents agreement of parties rather than <gloss
                        target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> fiat. I cannot believe it is “taking sides” to
                    ask parties to honor their commitments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AWR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Austin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
